english:
  title: Memorial to the Zhengdong Province
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The elders and officials of Goryeo, having purified ourselves through ritual ablution, humbly present this memorial to the honorable ministers and executives of the Zhengdong Province.

    When the imperial envoys, including Dojeok, arrived bearing the gracious amnesty proclaimed at the southern suburb sacrifice, our King Botap Sil-lin, leading his officials in full ceremonial regalia, went forth beyond the city walls to receive them and entered the provincial hall. After hearing the imperial edict read in full, the envoys seized the King, mounted him upon a horse, and departed with haste. The matter transpired so suddenly that even we attending ministers found ourselves without proper footing. What further words could we offer?

    Yet reflecting upon it, the King is young and inexperienced in such affairs—his actions flowed from innocence rather than intent. To understand his original purpose is to recognize no malice therein. The heavens above see all; how could they be deceived?

    Consider too that our kingdom's founding ancestor, the Wang clan, established our nation on these distant shores four hundred twenty-six years past. Through twenty-eight generations, sons have succeeded fathers. We maintained relations with Song, Liao, and Jin through official envoys, a mere vassal bond. When our Grand Progenitor, the Sagely Martial Emperor, rose to power, there came one called the Prince of Jingshan, who drove the people of the Central Plain before him, seeking to restore the fallen Liao. When his forces exhausted, he fled eastward to the islands and peninsulas. The Grand Progenitor dispatched generals Hazhen and Zhaala to punish this rebellion. Through bitter cold and deep snow, when provisions ran scarce, our King Zhongxian sent Zhao Chong and Kim Chu-ryeo with troops and grain. In a single stroke, the rebellion was crushed. Thus were our two nations bound in alliance, and our descendants shall not forget this day. We exchanged captives as tokens of faith—the "Khitan Fields" that remain in our kingdom testify to this.

    When the World Progenitor, the Cultured and Martial Emperor, reviewed his forces at Xiangyang, Ariqbuqa stirred rebellion in the northern steppes. The princes wavered in doubt, each considering whether to advance or retreat. Our King Zhongjing, then Crown Prince, braved frost and dew to journey straight to Bianliang to receive the Emperor upon the road. When the World Progenitor beheld him, he cried out in wonder and joy: "Goryeo, though distant and remote, sends its Crown Prince to greet me as I return from the north to assume the great succession! Surely Heaven aids me!"

    After King Zhongjing took the throne, the officials Lin Weimao and his son, displeased with our incorporation as a subject state, arbitrarily deposed and restored rulers, obstructing us from Ganghwa Island. The Crown Prince Zhonglieh hastened to inform the court. The World Progenitor, greatly angered, commanded the King's restoration and rode swiftly to the capital. The King and Crown Prince led their forces back eastward, captured and executed the rebels, abandoned the water routes for land, and with single-minded devotion served their duty.

    In the time of King Zhonglieh, when the World Progenitor twice sent expeditions against Japan, the King dispatched Kim Bang-gyeong and others to repair the war vessels, and they ever served as the vanguard. Moreover, when Hadan and the followers of Nayan attacked and conquered the lands of the Jurchen, and threatened to invade our borders, defying the heavenly authority, the King sent forth troops to meet them in battle and utterly defeated them—not a single chariot returned.

    In the final years of the Dade era, King Yikjiyeburhwa, aiding the Renzong Emperor in quelling rebellion and purifying the palace, received the honor of First-rank Meritorious Minister upon welcoming the Wuzong Emperor. This shows that the Wang clan has long been loyal to the court.

    Consider further that the World Progenitor bestowed upon a subject the Princess Hudukepmiisi, who bore King Yikjiyeburhwa. King Yikjiyeburhwa fathered King Anaptegsili. King Anaptegsili fathered King Botap Sil-ri. Though distant and remote in succession, King Botap Sil-ri nonetheless shares the bonds of flesh and blood with the World Progenitor.

    Moreover, the Empress Qi, born in our humble realm, became the consort of the supreme ruler and gave birth to the Crown Prince, for which the empire rejoiced. The court's treatment of our kingdom should surely differ from that of the barbarian nations.

    Our kingdom, separated from Japan by the sea, shares its fate as neighbors. When we receive fortune, they are shamed by their tardy submission; when we incur penalty, they are pleased by our stubborn delusion. Such is the nature of circumstances.

    In antiquity, Zhou imprisoned the Marquis of Wei yet ultimately restored him; Han summoned the King of Liang yet returned him to his state. Thus did these kings reveal their magnanimity. How much more so should our court, which since the succession of illustrious rulers has possessed virtue that abhors violence and loves life, surpassing even Zhou and Han?

    Yet now, having personally performed the suburban sacrifice, having united ancestor worship with heaven, and having completed the great rites, broadcasting virtue across the four seas, with dancing and rejoicing—if even one creature remains untouched by imperial benevolence, is this not a cause for sorrow?

    If only the Sage-Emperor, moved by that boundless compassion which forgives all transgression, would deign to turn his thoughts toward us. Should he release our King Botap Sil-ri from the bonds of guilt and allow him to swim in the waters of grace; should he permit the Wang clan to maintain their sovereign and state, to preserve their robes and customs and institutions; should he grant the simple folk of mountains and seas to dwell in peace upon their ancestral lands—then would not the intention of the Grand Progenitor and World Progenitor to cherish our humble kingdom shine ever brighter? Would not the World Progenitor's foresight in bestowing a princess to bind the hearts of distant peoples extend all the further? Would not the Empress's bearing of the Crown Prince and the empire's rejoicing and reliance grow ever more glorious? Would not our kingdom's loyalty and resolve to stand against enemies grow ever firmer? Would not the as-yet-unconquered people of Japan, casting off their stubborn blindness, delight in submission and drawing ever closer? Would not the spirits of four hundred twenty-six years and twenty-eight generations of descendants find ever deeper gratification? Would not the court's forgiveness of transgression and its boundless, life-cherishing virtue spread ever more widely throughout Heaven and Earth and to future ages?

    We humbly beseech you, esteemed ministers: take pity on these humble and lowly words and convey them to the Celestial Ear.
  footnotes:
    - 'Botap Sil-lin (寶塔實憐王): A young Goryeo king whose arrest during the reception of imperial envoys prompted this memorial of defense and appeal for clemency.'
    - 'The Khitan Fields (契丹場): Land granted to Goryeo as compensation and symbol of alliance following joint military action against the Jin dynasty.'
    - 'The four hundred twenty-six years and twenty-eight generations: A reference to Goryeo''s founding during the Later Three Kingdoms period and its continuous dynastic succession to the author''s time.'
    - 'The suburban sacrifice (郊天): A major imperial ritual performed at the southern suburb, representing the emperor''s renewal of the Mandate of Heaven.'
    - 'Empress Qi: A Goryeo princess who became empress of the Yuan court, cementing the bond between the two nations.'
